{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2015}} The '''Marin Municipal Water District''' (or '''MMWD''') is the government agency that provides drinking water to southern and central [[Marin County, California]]. Chartered in 1912, it became California's first municipal water district.<ref name=history>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinwater.org/controller?action=menuclick&id=397|title=MMWD|accessdate=July 25, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813210039/http://www.marinwater.org/controller?action=menuclick&id=397|archivedate=August 13, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It serves 195,000 people in a {{Convert|147|sqmi|km2|adj=on}} area that includes ten towns and cities.<ref name=about>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinwater.org/controller?action=menuclick&id=172|title=MMWD|accessdate=July 25, 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722115644/http://www.marinwater.org/controller?action=menuclick&id=172|archivedate=July 22, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>
==Reservoirs== The District's seven reservoirs in Marin County provide about 75% of the water it uses:<ref name=sources>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinwater.org/controller?action=menuclick&id=223 |title=MMWD |accessdate=July 25, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722115626/http://www.marinwater.org/controller?action=menuclick&id=223 |archivedate=July 22, 2010 |df= }}</ref> * [[Alpine Lake (Marin County, California)|Alpine Lake]], formed by Alpine Dam on [[Lagunitas Creek]] * [[Bon Tempe Lake]] on Lagunitas Creek * [[Kent Lake]], formed by Peters Dam on Lagunitas Creek * [[Lake Lagunitas]] on Lagunitas Creek * [[Nicasio Reservoir]], formed by Seeger Dam on [[Nicasio Creek]] * [[Phoenix Reservoir]] * [[Soulajule Reservoir]] on [[Arroyo Sausal]]
As of May 7, 2016, these 7 reservoirs stored 77,605 [[acre-feet]], which is 97.54% of capacity. The average storage for this date is 70,864 acre-feet, or 89.06%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.marinwater.org/300/Water-Watch|title=Water Watch|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>
==Recreation== Over {{Convert|21000|acres}} of land in District ownership are open to the public for recreational use from sunrise to sunset. There are {{Convert|130|mi}} of trails and unpaved roads available for hiking. The [[wikispot:marin:Cataract Falls|Cataract Falls Trail]] is one of the most popular trails. Many of the trails are also open for dog walking and horseback riding, while bicycling is only allowed on fire roads. Portions of the seven District reservoirs are open for [[hiking]], [[biking]], [[horseback riding]], [[fishing]], and [[picnicking]]. [[Camping]], [[Human swimming|swimming]], and [[boating]] are prohibited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marinwater.org/137/Watershed|title=Watershed|accessdate=May 17, 2016}}</ref>
==Administration== Its administrative offices are located at 220 Nellen Avenue in [[Corte Madera, California|Corte Madera]]: {{Coord|37|56|13|N|122|31|3|W|type:landmark_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}}.
