{{Infobox organization |name = Rural Power Company Limited |image = |image_border = |size = |alt = |caption = |map = |msize = |malt = |mcaption = |abbreviation = |motto = |formation = 31 December 1994 |extinction = |type = |status = |purpose = |headquarters = [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]] |location = |coords = <!-- Coordinates of location using a coordinates template --> |region_served = Bangladesh |members = |language = Bengali |leader_title = |leader_name = |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = |budget = |website = [http://rpcl.org.bd/ Rural Power Company Limited] |remarks = }}
'''Rural Power Company Limited''' is an autonomous government company responsible for rural electrification and power in Bangladesh and is located in [[Dhaka]], [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Govt to offload shares in 9 firms next year|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/news-detail-13735|accessdate=29 December 2017|work=The Daily Star|date=1 December 2007|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Smart power generation to ensure fuel efficiency|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/business/smart-power-generation-ensure-fuel-efficiency-1508152|accessdate=29 December 2017|work=The Daily Star|date=21 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>
==History== Rural Power Company Limited was established on 31 December 1994. It was the first independent power producer in Bangladesh not under the [[Bangladesh Power Development Board]]. The decision to form it was made by [[Executive Committee of the National Economic Council]] (ECNEC) on 23 November 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rural Power Company Limited (RPCL)|url=https://mpemr.gov.bd/power/details/35|website=mpemr.gov.bd|accessdate=28 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> It was formed by the Rural Electrification Board and is managed by a board of directors.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Khan|first1=Sharier|title=Honesty = Success, Dishonesty = Failure An overview of power sector unbundling in Bangladesh (1996-2006)|url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/forum/2007/january/honesty.htm|accessdate=28 December 2017|work=archive.thedailystar.net|publisher=Forum}}</ref> On 23 December 2004 it started work on a power plant in Savar in partnership with Dhaka North Power Project and Swiss company Alsthom despite specific instructions and opinions from the [[Power Cell]], [[Power Development Board]] and the [[Prime Minister's Office (Bangladesh)|Prime Minister's Office]]. [[Sigma Huda]] was its legal advisor.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Khan|first1=Sharier|title=RPCL's high-cost project to overcharge consumers|url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2004/12/23/d4122301011.htm|accessdate=29 December 2017|work=archive.thedailystar.net|publisher=The Daily Star}}</ref> Lahmeyer International Palli Power Services Limited sued the company in October 2005 in an arbitration court in Singapore over the cancellation of the Mymensingh 140-megawatt power plant.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lahmeyer sues RPCL for compensation|url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2005/10/12/d51012012822.htm|accessdate=29 December 2017|work=archive.thedailystar.net|publisher=The Daily Star}}</ref> Both companies had rivalries over the management of the power plant.<ref>{{cite news|title=140 MW Mymensing power plant shut down|url=https://bdnews24.com/bangladesh/2005/08/03/140-mw-mymensing-power-plant-shut-down|accessdate=29 December 2017|work=bdnews24.com}}</ref> The government of Bangladesh filed a case against the LIPPS chief AZ Rezaul Haq for attempting to sabotage the power plan and attempted to arrest him.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Khan|first1=Sharier|title=Power Plant Sabotage Cops raid office to nab Lahmeyer chief|url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2005/08/11/d5081101033.htm|accessdate=29 December 2017|work=archive.thedailystar.net|publisher=The Daily Star}}</ref>
